📑 Pattern 4: 2D Matrix Binary Search
Searching a grid where rows and columns are sorted.

The Concept: A strictly sorted M X N matrix can be visualized as a single 1D array of length M X N.
To convert the 1D mid index back into 2D grid coordinates:
row = mid / totalColumns
col = mid % totalColumns

Java Blueprint:
public boolean searchMatrix(int[][] matrix, int target) {
    int rows = matrix.length;
    int cols = matrix[0].length;
    
    int left = 0;
    int right = (rows * cols) - 1;
    
    while (left <= right) {
        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
        // Map 1D index to 2D coordinates
        int midValue = matrix[mid / cols][mid % cols];
        
        if (midValue == target) return true;
        else if (midValue < target) left = mid + 1;
        else right = mid - 1;
    }
    return false;
}

Essential Interview Questions:

Medium: Search a 2D Matrix (LeetCode 74) - Uses the math above.

Medium: Search a 2D Matrix II (LeetCode 240) - Rows and cols are sorted, but not strictly sequential. Start at the Top-Right corner. If target is larger, move down. If smaller, move left.

⚠️ The 3 Deadly Interview Traps
The Overflow Bug: Never write int mid = (left + right) / 2;. If left and right are massive numbers, adding them will overflow the 32-bit Integer limit, causing a negative index crash. Always use int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;.

Infinite Loops: If you use while (left < right) instead of <=, be very careful with how you assign left = mid vs left = mid + 1. If left and right are adjacent, mid rounds down to left. Setting left = mid will cause the loop to run forever.

Returning Early in "Bounds" Problems: When asked for the "Minimum", "First", or "Largest", finding a matching element does NOT mean you are done. Always save the result and continue shrinking the search space.
